One of the pastimes of the inhabitants of Viscara is a card game known as Rimer Cards.  It is simple to play, yet many enjoy the combination of luck, strategy, and planning.  Though shunned by those seeking the more visceral thrills of the combat pits, most residents are happy pitting imaginary creatures against each other. 

The goal of Rimer Cards is simple - defeat your player's avatar.  As the avatars are immobile game pieces with no combat ability, this can be a bit of a challenge.  Instead, cards are played by each side to summon creatures which do battle with your opponent's creatures and their avatar.  When one avatar falls, the game is over. 

An expert player is aware of the game's complexities.  Each creature card has a casting cost, as well as an attack and defense rating.  In order to play the card, you must have enough magic available to cover the card's casting cost. 

Magic is generated by magic generators, created by playing a magic generator card.  You can only play one generator per cycle, which limits the amount of magic you will have available to you early in the game. 

There are no clear turns in Creatures, as both players play cards continuously throughout play.  What limits the speed of the game are cycles.   At the beginning of every cycle, a new card is drawn for each player.  If a player has more than eight cards, one is randomly discarded.  Any magic generators that have had their power used up by casting spells will be replenished. It's also a time when additional magic generators may be put in play. 

At the beginning of the game, each player gets seven cards.  The first move of a game is to play a magic generator.  After the generator begins producing power, you can start summoning creatures.  You can summon as many creatures in your hand as you have magic from your generators.  Gameplay continues until one of the avatars is dead. 

There are non-creature cards you can play as well.  These spells are cast just like creature cards, but instead have a variety of effects on the game.  Read the descriptions carefully.

Certain cards can be sacrificed to produce different effects.  To sacrifice a creature, click on the gallows object to the left of the cards.
Rimer Cards - Rules of the Game
Angelic defenders boost the defense of nearby angels.
Though comparatively weak, these angels will heal your avatar a small amount each turn.
These tiny lights are the spirits of good souls who have given their lives to the cause of righteousness.
This valliant angelic warrior rallies other angels to her cause, boosting their attack abilities considerably.
Atlantians are spawned from the depths of the sea.  When cast, any free magic generators are used to boost the creatures abilities up to a maximum of five.
These divine beings are stalwart defenders of the faith.
These forest creatures are fierce protectors of their dens and best avoided.
Beholders strike fear into the hearts of their opponents, attacking with their massive jaws and stunning gaze.

Bone Golems are massive undead constructs, deadly and rugged.

Their presence also grants the lower skeletons a bonus in combat if they are nearby.
These fierce warriors care little about their own wounds, merely plunging into the fight.
The bulette is ponderous and well protected, an excellent creature to slow down the opposition.  Their bite is particularly effective against animals due to a unique venom.

Chaos witches care little for what sides they fight on.

Should one damage an opponent, they immediately switch sides.

Cougars have been known to attack even the largest of creatures.

The cougar can be sacrificed to deal 10 points of damage to all enemy creatures.

Most consider cows laughable beasts, but they do have a mighty kick when enraged.

The cow can be sacrificed to heal 1 point of damage to your avatar for every card you have in your hand.
Demon Knight can be sacrificed to inflict status effects upon all enemies within 10m.  The status inflicted is determined by the creature's distance in alignment from Chaotic Evil.

These immense creatures are incredibly tough and deadly.  Their immense size comes with a price, however.

When summoned, they will feed upon whatever morsels are handy.  50 hit points worth of creatures will be devoured.  If none are available, the dragon will take a bite directly out of the player's avatar.  It is wise to feed a waking dragon.
When the druid comes into play, all other animals except for rats gain bonuses to their attack and defense.
These proud warriors stand their ground firmly.
The Elder Fire Elemental is one of the most feared creatures in all the planes.

These fickle creatures of the woods are known tricksters and best avoided.  While in play, drains a point of magic from both players' available magic generators.  If either player has no magic generators, then the Fairy Dragon will switch sides to attack the player with no generators.  If both players have no magic generators, then Fairy Dragon will self-sacrifice, and have its sacrifice effect played on both players.

Sacrifice Fairy Dragon to automatically play a randomly selected card from your hand, with a magic cost of up to 2.  Any pumpable casting cost cards played in this manner will consume all magic available as though they had been cast normally, though their initial cost of one magic will be free.
Feral rats are tougher and more vicious than their weaker kin.
These enormous spiders have a poisonous bite and a rugged carapace.
Goblins are the grunts of any army, plentiful and eager to fight.
Goblin crossbows are smaller than their human varieties, though just as deadly.
Goblin shaman are the long-range casters of the goblin horde.  Though weak, their spells can cause problems for advancing armies.
When the goblin warlord comes into play, all other goblins gain bonuses to their attack and defense.

Often scoffed at by those more knowlegable in the arts, the goblin witchdoctor has skills unknown in more learned circles.

Owner of the Witchdoctor may sacrifice the highest defense value creature he currently controls to the Witchdoctor to heal his avatar of a number of hit points equal to the maximum hit points of the sacrificed creature.  This ability may not take the avatar above their maximum hit point total.  This ability is controlled by selecting the Witchdoctor from the sacrifice placeable.  Doing so does not destroy the Witchdoctor, but deals an amount of damage to the Witchdoctor equal to a half of the amount of healing provided.
Hill Giants wield massive clubs and can soak up a huge amount of damage.

This freakish creature seeks to kill for pleasure whenever possible.

Owner of the Hook Horror may sacrifice the highest attack value creature he currently controls to the Hook Horror to deal an amount of damage equal to half the maximum hit points of the sacrificed creature to the opponent's avatar, and to the Hook Horror.  This ability is controlled by selecting the Hook Horror from the sacrifice placeable.  Doing so does not destroy the Hook Horror.

These bizarre creatures feed off the thoughts of the living.

Sacrifice Intellect Devourer to remove four random cards from the opponents undrawn cards, and two random cards from your own undrawn cards.
The Kobold Chief has an aura that grants any kobolds around him the effects of the Potion of Heroism spell.
Lays down mines in periods of one game turn.  Carries four mines in total.  Mines will detonate five seconds after a non-kobold steps into their trigger zone.
Can be sacrificed to create a 3 point fireball effect.

One game round after being brought into play, if still alive, will jump up into the air and land on either the enemy avatar, or the highest attack rating creature.  Impact will kill the Kobold, but will deal a fixed amount of damage to the target.

When a necromancer takes the final step and transforms into a lich, they gain great powers over the undead.

When a lich enters play, all other undead gain bonuses to their attack and defense.
Loremasters are useless in battle, but have the great power of allowing an additional draw per turn.  The down side is that they require the use of two magic generators to maintain their existence.

Magic generators are key to your success in this game.

In order to generate magic to cast your spells, these must be put into play.  You may only put one in play each cycle, so you won't be able to immediately empty your hand once play starts.  Also, the magic that they generate slowly recharges, so cast your spells carefully.
Useless in combat, a Maiden of Paradise can be sacrificed to produce three additional points of magic.

Champion of the Blood Wars, a striding figure of destruction, Ark'Neth is capable of laying waste to all those around him.

Ark'Neth can be sacrificed to inflict status effects upon all enemies within 10m.  The status inflicted is determined by the creature's distance in alignment from Chaotic Evil.  Does not die when triggered.  Only one Ark'Neth may be in play at one time.
Can trigger his sacrifice effect to cause all standard kobolds on the playing field to become Kobold Pogosticks.  This effect does not kill Deekin.

An angel of light, a warrior for hope and all that is good, Jysirael stands as a beacon of light against the darkness of evil.  Only one Jysirael can be in play at any time.

Can trigger a sacrifice effect to fully heal all friendly summons within a 10m radius.  Using this ability does not kill Jysirael, but does reduce her hit points by half.

Saeshen is the queen of the jungle, the ruler of the faeries, and a magical trickster of legendary status.

During the upkeep phase, automatically brings the topmost fairy dragon in the discard pile back into play.
Pain golems have the unusual ability to cause damage directly to the player's avatar.  For every card over four they hold, your opponent will take two points of damage.
Phase Spider phases out of the game every other turn.

Pit Fiends are the most deadly creature possible, but the caster pays a heavy price bringing it into battle.  When cast, two magic generators are destroyed.  
Every turn after that, they destroy a player's magic generator.  If there are none to destroy, it will switch sides and the opponent must pay the cost.
This abomination of a rat carries such a virulent plague that all non-rat creatures in the game will constantly take damage from this deforming disease.
Though rats are easily dispatched, they have a nasty bite that can cause disease.
When the rat king comes into play, all other rats gain bonuses to their attack and defense.

Sacrifice revenant to kill the highest attack rating non-undead creature owned by the enemy.

During upkeep cycle, if alive, drains life from the avatar.  During upkeep, if in discard pile with one other creature card above it, automatically returns to play.  Doing so destroys the creature card from the discard pile.  If discarded from players hand, Revenant is removed from the game.

Sea Hags are tricksters who dabble in dark magics, making them particularly effective against vermin of all kinds.
Sewer rats are one step above typical rats, a bit more fierce but vermin all the same.
The shadow assassin can be sacrificed to destroy the enemy's strongest creature.
Skeletal archers are frail, but quite accurate with their bows.
Skeletal warriors are the grunts of any undead army.

Each turn, a solar stone will destroy a random card from the opponent's undrawn cards.  Also, two points of magic are required to maintain the stone.  Should it not be available, the solar stone will be destroyed.
Enchants all angels with an attack and defence boosting effect, that increases in effect when more angels are on the field.
This spell is first cast on your avatar, then it finds the toughest of your creatures and boosts their defense considerably.
This spell will cause the strongest of your enemy's creatures to be instantly slain.
This spell will cause the strongest of your enemy's creatures to be instantly returned to their hand.

When cast, up to five corpses are cleared from the battlefield, their essence in life converted into healing for the caster.

If five corpses are on the field, they will all be consumed regardless of the player's health.
This spell removes all enchantments from all creatures in the game, as well as any global card-spells in play.
When cast, all available magic energy flows into the spell, healing your avatar in proportion to the number of powered generators you possess.
When cast, each turn, both players will be drained of an amount of power equal to the maximum hand size minus the current number of cards in hand.  Additional castings will add one to this value.

All beholders that the caster controls will use special eye ray attacks. These will target individual opponents, starting with the highest attack creature the enemy controls.  If the enemy has less creatures than you have beholders, they will target the avatar.
Spell - Eye of the Beholder, cost 2

This spell creates a ring of fire around the target that deals 1d4 + 1 fire damage to any who strike the recipient.  Targets start with the avatar, and then move on to the highest defence creature you own.

This spell launches a fireball at your enemy's avatar, damaging all nearby enemy creatures.  This spell automatically uses up all available magic you possess.  With each available generator, the power of the blast increases.

This terrible spell was once thought lost forever.  Once cast, only a Dispel Magic can remove it.  Each turn, damage is dealt to each players' avatars and creatures equal to the total number of power generators in play on both sides.  Should more than one Flux be cast, even more damage will be dealt.
Casting this spell will heal your avatar if it is injured.  If it isn't hurt, it will heal the most damaged creature instead.

The Higher Calling spell lays an enchantment across the battlefield, affecting all powerful creatures with a siren's call that slows them in battle.  The lesser beasts are unaffected and Dispel Magic removes the enchantment.
This spell finds the strongest of your creatures and boosts their attack considerably.

This spell drains a small amount of life from the living creatures in play and gives their energy to your avatar.  The more magic generators available, the more creatures can be affected.  Note that it doesn't work on undead creatures.

This spell fires a single lightning bolt at your opponent.  If any enemy creatures are on the battlefield, they are targeted first.  If there are none, the blast goes directly at your opponent's avatar.

When cast, the highest attack rating creature of the opponent switches sides.  The cost of this spell is the cost of the target creature plus one.  If not enough power is available for the highest attack rating creature, finds one with a lower cost.
This spell returns one card from the discard pile to the casters hand.
When cast, the most powerful of your opponent's creatures will become paralyzed.
This spell grants the recipient a +5 attack bonus, +50 temporary hit points, and a haste effect for two game rounds.  Targets highest attack creatures first.

When this enchantment is in place, all players draw an additional card.

The effects of this enchantment are cumulative.  For example, if cast twice, two extra cards are drawn.  A Dispel Magic spell will remove all Power Stream effects in play.
This spell raises the most powerful of your dead creatures to fight in battle once again.
Casting this spell results in the destruction of one of your opponent's magic generators.
Casting this spell kills all creatures and removes all corpses from play.
Creates a clone of the highest attack creature the opponent has in play for you.  Dispel Magic will destroy the clone.

This whirlwind disrupts magic across a wide area.  While Vortex is in play, only half of both players' available magic generators will be restored of power at the beginning of each turn.  Additional Vortex effects will increase the reduction by increasing the size of division.  Ie. the first Vortex will 1/2 the available power, the second will reduce it to 1/3, then 1/4, 1/5, etc.  A Dispel Magic spell will remove all Vortex effects in play.
When cast, ownership of all creatures is swapped.  Additionally, all of the caster's magic generators are destroyed.

Every creature the caster controls gets a boost to attack and defense equal to the number of creatures the caster controls.  Needless to say, for players with large numbers of creatures, this spell is quite powerful.
Spell - Wrath of the Horde, cost 4

Spirit Guardians are employed to confuse or fend off the enemy, as they are insubstantial and difficult to hit, though doing no damage.

Spirit Guardians can be sacrificed to heal 30 points of damage to your avatar.

Steel Guardians are incredibly tough, soaking up huge amounts of damage, though clumsy in combat.

Steel Guardians radiate an aura that increases the defense of any nearby creatures, including your avatar.
Troglodytes are cruel warriors, preferring to attack enemies in large groups.  They have a particular hatred for goblins and are especially effective against them.

These subterranean beasts have a powerful shell and nasty bite, not to mention a stunning gaze.

The Umber Hulk can be sacrificed to briefly paralyze all opponents.

Vampires are known for their vicious bite and toughness.

Also, should a vampire succeed in killing their opponent, they will be greatly strengthened.

If a vampire master kills a creature, a vampire will be raised to join the fight.  There is a cost to this card, however.  Every turn, they drain a small measure of life from the avatar in order to feed his great hunger.
This mythical beast is the defender of the forests, powerful in spiritual magics.
The white wolf enhances nearby wolves, making them quick and agile in combat.
These predators often hunt in packs, providing an attack bonus to others of their kind.
Zombies, while frail and weak, have the uncanny ability to repair all damage to themselves after consuming the flesh of those they have killed.
Zombie lords enhance the attack and defense of nearby zombies.  Furthermore, should they kill an enemy, they gain additional attack, defense, and hit points.
